# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: inverurie-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] It takes its name from the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which had substantially different boundaries.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Aberdeenshire Council area includes all of the areas of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire except the area making up Aberdeen City Council area, as well as part of Banffshire.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The historic county boundaries are still officially used for a few purposes, namely land registration and lieutenancy.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire Council is headquartered at Woodhill House in Aberdeen, making it the only Scottish council whose headquarters are located outside its jurisdiction.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeen itself forms a different council area (Aberdeen City).
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire borders onto Angus and Perth and Kinross to the south, Highland and Moray to the west and Aberdeen City to the east.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Traditionally, it has depended economically on the primary sector (agriculture, fishing, and forestry) and related processing industries.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Over the last 40 years, the development of the oil and gas industry and associated service sector has broadened Aberdeenshire's economic base, and contributed to a rapid population growth of some 50% since 1975.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Its land represents 8% of Scotland's overall territory.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] It covers an area of 6,313 square kilometres (2,437 sq mi).
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a rich prehistoric and historical heritage.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] It is the locus of a large number of Neolithic and Bronze Age archaeological sites, including Longman Hill, Kempstone Hill, Catto Long Barrow and Cairn Lee.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The area was settled in the Bronze Age by the Beaker culture, who arrived from the south around 2000–1800 BC.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Stone circles and cairns were constructed predominantly in this era.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Around the 1st century AD, the Taexali people, who left little history, were believed to have resided along the coast.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Picts were the next documented inhabitants of the area and were no later than 800–900 AD.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Romans also were in the area during this period, as they left signs at Kintore.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Christianity influenced the inhabitants early on, and there were Celtic monasteries at Old Deer and Monymusk.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Since medieval times, there have been many traditional paths that crossed the Mounth (a spur of mountainous land that extends from the higher inland range to the North Sea slightly north of Stonehaven) through present-day Aberdeenshire from the Scottish Lowlands to the Highlands.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Some of the most well known and historically important trackways are the Causey Mounth and Elsick Mounth.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire played an important role in the fighting between the Scottish dynasties.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] During the Anglo-Norman penetration, other families arrive, such as House of Balliol, Clan Bruce, and Clan Cumming (Comyn).
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] During the Scottish Wars of Independence, the King of England Edward I travelled across the area twice with his invading army, in 1296 and 1303.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] In 1307, Robert the Bruce was victorious near Inverurie.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] These new families set the stage for the upcoming rivalries during the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] This rivalry grew worse during and after the Protestant Reformation when religion was another reason for conflict between the clans.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The Gordon family adhered to Catholicism and the Forbeses to Protestantism.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire was the historic seat of the clan Dempster.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Three universities were founded in the area prior to the 17th century, King's College in Old Aberdeen (1494), Marischal College in Aberdeen (1593), and the University of Fraserburgh (1592).
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] During the 17th century, Aberdeenshire was the location of more fighting, centred on the Marquess of Montrose and the Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] This period also saw increased wealth due to the increase in trade with Germany, Poland, and the Low Countries.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] After the end of the Revolution of 1688, an extended peaceful period was interrupted only by fleeting events such as the Rising of 1715 and the Rising of 1745.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The latter resulted in the end of the ascendancy of Episcopalianism and the feudal power of landowners.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] An era began of increased agricultural and industrial progress.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The present council area is named after the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which has different boundaries and ceased to be used for local government purposes in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Local government functions were shared between the two levels.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The modern council area was created in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] It covers the combined area of the Banff and Buchan, Gordon, and Kincardine and Deeside districts that had been created in 1975.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The present Aberdeenshire Council area therefore consists of all of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire (except the area of those two counties making up Aberdeen City), as well as the north-east portions of Banffshire.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The population of the council area has risen over 50% since 1971 to approximately 265,080 in 2024, representing 4.7% of Scotland's total.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's population has increased by 9.1% since 2001, while Scotland's total population grew by 3.8%.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The census lists a relatively high proportion of under 16s and slightly fewer working-age people compared with the Scottish average.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is one of the most homogeneous/indigenous regions of the UK.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] In 2011, 82.2% of residents identified as 'White Scottish', followed by 12.3% who are 'White British', whilst ethnic minorities constitute only 0.9% of the population.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The largest ethnic minority group is Asian Scottish/British at 0.8%.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] In addition to the English language, 48.8% of residents reported being able to speak and understand the Scots language.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,382 residents aged three and over, 121,797 (47.5%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] This is the greatest proportion of Scots speakers of any Scottish council area.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,377 residents aged three and over, 3,579 (1.4%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is estimated at £3,496M (2011), representing 5.2% of the Scottish total.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy is closely linked to Aberdeen City's (GDP £7,906M), and in 2011, the region as a whole was calculated to contribute 16.8% of Scotland's GDP.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Between 2012 and 2014, the combined Aberdeenshire and Aberdeen City economic forecast GDP growth rate is 8.6%, the highest growth rate of any local council area in the UK and above the Scottish rate of 4.8%.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] A significant proportion of Aberdeenshire's working residents commute to Aberdeen City for work, varying from 11.5% from Fraserburgh to 65% from Westhill.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Average Gross Weekly Earnings (for full-time employees employed in workplaces in Aberdeenshire in 2011) are £572.60.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the Scottish average by £2.10 and a fall of 2.6% on the 2010 figure.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The average gross weekly pay of people resident in Aberdeenshire is much higher, at £741.90, as many people commute out of Aberdeenshire, principally into Aberdeen City.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Total employment (excluding farm data) in Aberdeenshire is estimated at 93,700 employees (Business Register and Employment Survey 2009).
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The majority of employees work within the service sector, predominantly in public administration, education and health.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Almost 19% of employment is within the public sector.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy remains closely linked to Aberdeen City's and the North Sea oil industry, with many employees in oil-related jobs.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] The average monthly unemployment (claimant count) rate for Aberdeenshire in 2011 was 1.5%.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the average rate of Aberdeen City (2.3%), Scotland (4.2%) and the UK (3.8%).
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] In the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'No' by a percentage of 60.4%.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] In the 2016 European Union membership referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'Remain' by the third lowest margin of 55.0%.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] First and second lowest margin for 'Remain' were Moray (50.1%) and Dumfries and Galloway (53.1%).
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] There are numerous rivers and burns in Aberdeenshire, including Cowie Water, Carron Water, Burn of Muchalls, River Dee, River Don, River Ury, River Ythan, Water of Feugh, Burn of Myrehouse, Laeca Burn and Luther Water.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Numerous bays and estuaries are found along the seacoast of Aberdeenshire, including Banff Bay, Ythan Estuary, Stonehaven Bay and Thornyhive Bay.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a marine west coast climate on the Köppen climate classification.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is in the rain shadow of the Grampians, therefore it has a generally dry climate for a maritime region, with portions of the coast receiving 25 inches (64 cm) of moisture annually.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Summers are mild, and winters are typically cold in Aberdeenshire; Coastal temperatures are moderated by the North Sea such that coastal areas are typically cooler in the summer and warmer in the winter than inland locations.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aberdeenshire] Coastal areas are also subject to haar, or coastal fog.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:inverurie-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:inverurie-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Chalmers Hospital was founded by Alexander Chalmers (died 11 August 1835), a merchant of Banff, who left the whole of his estate to be applied, upon the death of his wife, towards funding and building a hospital for the people in the Royal Burgh of Banff.
[src:inverurie-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Mrs Chalmers died in 1861, and Chalmers Hospital opened on 19 July 1864.
[src:inverurie-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The original 'deed of mortification' set out that this was for any destitute sick persons born, domiciled or resident in the Banff area, although in 1929 the trustees successfully petitioned for the removal of this restriction.
[src:inverurie-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Some major redevelopment work began in October 2008, after the hospital attracted criticism for not being up to date, with some of the interior features having been there since the Second World War.
[src:inverurie-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital remained open during the work, although the Findlater ward services were moved to Campbell Hospital in Portsoy until the Findlater ward was refurbished, and Seafield and Deveron ward were merged.
[src:inverurie-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The midwifery unit was demolished and rebuilt to provide modern facilities.
[src:inverurie-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Numerous other internal changes were also made inside, including X-ray facilities being moved to a different area of the building.
[src:inverurie-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The redevelopment also provided upgraded facilities for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy and podiatry.
[src:inverurie-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The completion of the redevelopment was recognised with a visit by the Princess Royal in March 2012.
[src:inverurie-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital is supported by GPs from Banff, Gamrie, Deveron, Macduff, Portsoy and Aberchirder Medical Practices.
[src:inverurie-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] The facility, which was designed by William Smith, was established as an infectious diseases hospital in 1874.
[src:inverurie-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] It was significantly expanded in 1895 and a new nurses' home was completed in 1931.
[src:inverurie-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] During the 1964 Aberdeen typhoid outbreak, over 400 cases were diagnosed and the patients were quarantined at the City Hospital and Woodend Hospital, although no fatalities resulted.
[src:inverurie-hospital/inverurie-hospital] The hospital has its origins in an infectious diseases hospital in Cunninghill Road which opened in January 1897.
[src:inverurie-hospital/inverurie-hospital] It moved to a new 60-bed facility in Upperboat Road, which was designed by R.
[src:inverurie-hospital/inverurie-hospital] It continued to deal with a wide range of infectious diseases from across Aberdeenshire.
[src:inverurie-hospital/inverurie-hospital] Following the eradication of many infectious diseases, single storey wards were re-designated for general medicine in 1958.
[src:inverurie-hospital/inverurie-hospital] The Minor Injury Unit Service in Inverurie is delivered by Inverurie Medical Practice at the Inverurie Health and Social Care Hub, during the hours of 8.30am-6pm Monday to Friday.
[src:inverurie-hospital/inverurie-hospital] There is no longer an out of hours Minor Injury Unit Service provided at Inverurie Hospital.
